    <body>
      <pb n="1"/>
      <p>
        <hi rend="underline">Confidential</hi>
      </p>
      <p rend="align(right)">
        <placeName>New York</placeName>
        <date>February 8<hi rend="sup">th</hi> 5614.</date>
      </p>
      <p>Rev<hi rend="sup">d</hi>
        <persName>Isaac Leeser</persName></p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">Esteemed Friend</p>
      <p rend="indent(2)">Enclosed in an “effusion” of<lb/> a “theme” <sic>sensatively</sic>
        affecting the “environs” of my heart; which<lb/> I send to you by the “south west passage”
        to <placeName>Philadelphia</placeName><lb/> for publication, provided you deem it fit to
        grace the pages<lb/> of The Occident. If you conclude to present it I should<lb/> feel
        obliged by your correcting any errors either in <sic>grammer</sic> or<lb/> punctuation which
        your practiced eye will readily discov<add>er</add></p>
      <p rend="indent(1)">Should you differ with my views, and think it necessary<lb/> to oppose
        them I beg you will do so, in such a strain as<lb/> will not give my adversaries any cause
        for exultation.<lb/> If you think the opinions expressed by me, would afford<lb/> my enemies
        a good weapon to lay hold of, especially<lb/> at the present time, you will please return
        the M. S.<lb/> to me: but as I consider “Prayer the railroad” to Heaven<lb/> and wishing to
        keep the “Car upon the track” I have in my<lb/> “coruscant effusion” gently alluded to the
        reckless speed of<lb/> our Modern prayer sayers and at the same time paid<lb/> a high and
        deserved compliment to those “pious men<lb/> of ancient days.” I trust you will not
        consider<lb/> my “Rail Road” Metaphor an infringement upon the<lb/> patent of the “North
        West line” or that I desire to<lb/> start an opposition to that road heavenward: yet<lb/> I
        am candid enough to admit I believe my road<lb/> if properly constructed would offer as good
        accomo–<lb/>–dations to the bestowed of charity as the North West./</p>
    </body>
